The Republican Strategy to Resist Obama's Re-Election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
But the Brennan Center considers the latter myth to be a myth, arguing that electoral fraud in the United States is rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
Moreover, Republican lawyers have counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in a decade.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the US.
That is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to show photo ID and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will, and deprive citizens with a criminal record of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no US state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The US Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
Republican officials were quick to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states requiring voters to show photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of Americans, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government agency.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
And the cost of obtaining the required ID often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that is not all.
Student voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, those same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly Republican, to use the cards issued by those clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of US citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are US citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at restricting the voting of Hispanics.
Two-thirds of Hispanic voters are thought to vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers introduced laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wished to register.
This restriction has not been without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, a voter registration campaign helped to register some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17% drop in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
In the 2008 general election in Florida, for example, 33% of early voters were African-Americans, even though the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same was true of Hispanics.
Representing only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who made up 76% of voters, only 46% voted early.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has helped to limit some of the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws requiring photo identification.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics decry the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as an apparent effort to influence the outcome of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that have enacted these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: get tested or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes produces false results, false positives, and sometimes false positives, leading to useless medical interventions.
Men who are already reluctant to undergo screening have much more reason to hesitate.
Pass the test or not?
We asked two experts for their opinion.
In studies conducted in the United States, there have been many cases among study groups, so the data are difficult to interpret and it is difficult to make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time in Europe, found differences in mortality rates between patients who were screened and those who were not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of follow-up, that those who did not undergo screening were 30-40% more likely to develop metastases.
Therefore, I would recommend taking the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if a direct relative has prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer has been detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to be made aware of his or her cancer risk by offering him or her options, without necessarily treating prostate cancer, which is not life-threatening in the long term, and choosing, in these cases, to actively monitor the disease.
Today, many men diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is neither aggressive nor life-threatening.
We will offer them active follow-up, and if the disease progresses, we will initiate treatment.
Increasingly, we are defining with precision the criteria for deciding who should or should not receive treatment.
So I would recommend taking the test anyway.
But it is also important to consult your doctor to determine whether or not to take this test.
