Prevent disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite advances in scientific research, maintaining a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of the disease.
It is estimated that if all people ate healthily and exercised enough, 30% of cancer cases could be prevented.
"If no one smoked anymore, that figure would rise to at least 50%," said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Association.
However, it is estimated that 10% of cancer cases are hereditary.
Several types of cancer remain completely unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Association, the fight against smoking remains a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is associated with 85% of lung cancer cases.
And it is a risk factor for many others.
It causes enormous damage to people's health.
"Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouragingly, 10 years after giving up smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is halved.
Weight
Overweight and obesity also contribute to the disease, according to the CAR.
They increase the risk of breast, colorectal, oesophagus, pancreas, and uterus cancer.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colon cancer," the association added.
Nutrition
The association also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of colon cancer.
Sausages should also be avoided.
Preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage cells in the body and lead to the development of cancer," the Association explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, many scientists have been studying the effects of vitamin supplements on cancer.
But, so far, the results of these studies have been mixed.
According to the SCC, vitamin E studies are yielding mixed results.
While one showed a reduction in the risk of prostate cancer, the other had the opposite effect.
Estimating the impact of vitamin D on cancer development is also unclear.
However, Mr Beaulieu emphasises that it is important to discuss your concerns and family history with your doctor.
"Taking a test does not lead to cancer."
The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer's announcement that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a stir - and with good reason.
This boson is thought to explain the mass of all particles in the universe, nothing less.
It is also the last particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or at least "least imperfect," description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not previously been scientifically detected.
But physicists are not yet entirely sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, though some data are not yet conclusive.
Let's assume, however, that it is the Higgs boson, because the chances of it being mistaken seem minimal, and see what that means.
There is, in this world, one inescapable law that says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way around this rule, don't even try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
But while particle physics is a strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consists, in general terms, of some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called fermions, who prudently obey Pauli's principle.
On the other are bosons, a heinous gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not this principle, which means that they can comfortably be in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratory's Particle Adventure site (quite extraordinary, by the way), these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "force particles," by which the main forces of nature are propagated, and to which the Higgs boson in some ways belongs.
These very bosons, it should be stressed, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: the photon, or "light particle," which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when one particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that particular place, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the "force carrier" bosons.
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for the boson to appear.
But the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could be shaken only by a very large rock.
That is why a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - is needed to achieve such huge energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact; others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to the fridge itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So what "can all this research bring," Ms Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to test the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to detect discrepancies between observations and SM predictions.
Moreover, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be revealed, because the slightest discrepancy could open the door to a "new physics" and plug some of the Model's holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (ooh!) or for the dark matter that forms roughly 80% of the universe (ooh!).
But, so far, no such discrepancies have been found at CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that they do not exist.
Look: in the very early 1960 "s, the pioneers of laser research at Bell Laboratories could not have imagined the revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous were pulsed) in 1962, said that initially the laser was seen more as a "laboratory gadget."
Imagine...
In addition, an app can be found for the tools that accompany the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his 1969 optical research.
This sensor, though it was not its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows that anything can happen.
Palliative care is the best way to die... | "Debt"
The delicate issue of the end of life was recently discussed at the Commission for Dignity in Quebec.
The debate is due to resume soon, while a bill is being drafted.
Nevertheless, much remains to be done in this critical area.
"Debt" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him from within gave him a two-year reprieve.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, between life and death, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"But it's always a shock, you can't prepare for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet or even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a mouth-watering lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to eat.
He is cheerful, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medication, take him to the bath.
Courage in the face of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish for me to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating," he admits.
A few hours later, staff found a cure for the disease.
"Throughout our lives, we are taught that a man must urinate standing up," says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
To regress to the state of a child is, for some, an unbearable humiliation.
"It all depends on a person's ability" to accept decline, he argues.
For, according to many people involved in palliative care, important events happen even in the midst of this decline.
Patients who are admitted to Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all have cancer.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months to live.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses is no longer providing what is called "curative" care.
Mrs A., 89, is most afraid of dying "conscious from asphyxiation."
But the illness allowed me to get to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't want anything else in life," she says, before allowing herself to be put on a breathing mask.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy, in the coming days.
At the Victor-Gadbois shelter, a group of volunteers provides body care and nutritional assistance.
This is palliative care, which remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care place for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That is very little, given that, sooner or later, we will all die.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr Christian Martel, one of the shelter's doctors.
Whether it's physical comfort, emotional comfort, or emotional comfort.
To a dying person, we will agree to provide mouth rinses of brandy or Pepsi, whatever he asks.
Diabetics are no longer forced to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought a beer to Mr X, who died tonight.
In the morning, his son had a beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as well as patients," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the Victor-Gadbois shelter, no day is like the previous one.
Next to a 93-year-old man who is enjoying his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows as he toasts in his honour, a 36-year-old man, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, who has tried everything to survive, dies tragically.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The challenge of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is the care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stages of their lives, whether at home, in hospital or in a care home.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is this large gap in Quebec's health-care system that makes many palliative care doctors wary of a law legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by palliative care luminaries Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, indicating their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health-care system is not efficient enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, "I saw a patient who had spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one had taken the necessary steps to alleviate it.
I fear that patients want to die simply because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists are trying to save patients until the last day, despite the pessimistic prognosis.
Helen Richard's hopes of survival were already slim when she stopped her gruelling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was stopping the fight, "she says.
At the same time, she told me that my days were numbered!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr Martel estimates that 90 per cent of patients who ask to die thank medical staff for not complying with their request after the palliative care team alleviates their pain.
It should be noted, however, that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in dealing with pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, palliative care director at the Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are resistant to anesthesia in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until he or she dies, either intermittently or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we are unaware of this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Pain sufferers always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanised," it means "I want to be relieved."
