Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Day after day, highway officials, construction contractors, political party fund-raisers, and Italian mafia specialists tell what they know about the colossal "system" that is entangling the construction industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists, and mafioso.
An "industry" that cost Quebec taxpayers dearly, especially in 1990 and 2000.
"It's curious how this system crumbles after all the money has been put into the case," jokes Jacques Duchesneau, a deputy and former Montreal police chief.
It was thanks to him that a scandal erupted in 2011 as a by-product of an investigation into malfeasance related to road construction contracts in Quebec, to which the Liberal prime minister at the time, Jean Charet, reluctantly agreed.
The Duchesne Report established a direct link between industry, covert financing of political parties, and corruption.
"Since the investigation began in 2010," he points out, "the Department of Transportation alone would have saved a billion dollars in contracts" if some had curbed their instincts to take a stake.
The Charbonneau Commission "has already removed two mayors," he adds, hoping that it will "uncover the schemes behind individuals."
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, established in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, created in 2011, has joined the case, with an extensive staff of government auditors, investigators, and analysts.
And then there are the members of the special unit, the Hammers, who, after 2009, forced the Montreal wastewater cartel to stop inflating the value of contracts.
In recent weeks, a series of searches have been carried out and some municipal officials, such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, the mayor of a small town, have been charged with fraud and corruption.
Next in line is Gilles Vaillancourt, who recently resigned as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of repeatedly accepting bribes in the awarding of public contracts.
In addition, several Montreal railway engineers and Italian-born construction contractors, including Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, have been formally charged.
The latter detonated a real bomb, telling the investigators about the "system" of obtaining government contracts.
For several years, Zambito gave 3% of the value of Montreal contracts to a mafia-linked middleman, who in turn transferred money to Mayor Gerald Tremblay's United Montreal party.
In the 2000s, Zambito poured money left and right. He transferred more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to various parties in the province, mostly the Liberals then in power.
He also admitted illegally raising funds for former Liberal Deputy Prime Minister Nathalie Normando.
Sewerage contracts that inflated costs
In Montreal, the corruption "system" worked smoothly.
Gilles Surprenant, a former civil engineer, described it in detail before the commission: over a period of ten years, he received gifts, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey matches, and bribes totalling $736,000 from construction firms in exchange for sewage contracts that he inflated.
Other officials in charge of road construction have admitted that they got away with inflating bills by 30-40% with bogus add-ons.
Then, one organizer from the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to the existence of a parallel budget that filled party coffers with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a deep crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first deputies in Montreal to sound the alarm.
Mayor of the Rivière-de-Prairie district in the east of the island, she has opposed since 2010 the sale of a municipal plot bought for $5 million and resold for... $1.6 million to developers at the height of the construction boom.
70% of dirty money in election campaigns
She says that in the investigation that will eventually be launched, she will "pull a thread to understand the functioning of a system infested with ants to stop gangrene and identify those responsible."
She describes the process as "painful but positive."
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but Montreal will need its own investigative team and an observer to avoid a return of questionable practices.
How we clean at home.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau notes for his part that "officials stole hundreds of millions of dollars," but he is particularly concerned about the role of "elected officials who knew about the scheme" but were not involved in the fraud.
Given that dirty money accounts for 70% of campaign finance in Quebec, he jokes: "I was told it was just a pale reflection of reality."
The Quebec government is proposing to limit donations to parties to $100, but he says this will not change the situation: "Until we strictly limit electoral spending, there will be dirty money in politics."
He calls for a complete overhaul of the system for awarding public contracts and party funding: "We cannot go lower; having the courage to get to the bottom of things, we can build a house on firmer foundations, with better control and the rule of law."
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau encourages those who laugh to look in their own backyard...
