Pay and Sell Without Banks - With Bitcoin
It is the opposite of the current monetary exchange, which is based on central banks numbering transactions between receiving parties with processing fees.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, the political vision is clear: the belief that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows file sharing among peer-to-peer participants.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been logged from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin, which peaked at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to around $10 today (rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its report on virtual currencies published in October, took an interest in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as the "credits" used to advance in a video game that are earned in the course of the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchanges are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously ledger holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, the solution of which, like a temporary central bank, is granted the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hashing phase of a file, that is, the transformation of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it, before "hashing" it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus appears to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would alter the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, a user were willing to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), only one of these two transactions would be validated by the network - and the other would remain unvalidated because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred million, which leaves a reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The network has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing Bitcoin services have been attacked, and bitcoins have been stolen from reserves.
"The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noizat, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Big players such as Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
A "giant sell-off" was announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, another author of the currency manual, is a firm believer in the technology's potential as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or a contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is thus cheaper.
The holder has better control over his or her personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat clarifies, assuring that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to rethink hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
"It will be some time before Bitcoin takes hold, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, proposes, incidentally, to reconsider the various risks that are now considered to be elevated if the system succeeds.
We have withdrawn from Afghanistan.
What next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans are due to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain control of its territory, and for Afghans to choose their future without relying on us alone.
We suffered mainly from Afghan peasants, whom we regarded as terrorists.
And we ourselves, with the 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded and maimed.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former commanders hiding in Pakistan, but also often peasants who reject the presence of a foreign army, as was the case under the USSR.
They want to protect their traditions, old and archaic, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, and Tajiks.
They are tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, but they will no longer exist once the West becomes more delicate.
The withdrawal of French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French loans, went smoothly.
Convoys of trucks and armoured vehicles, accompanied by helicopters, reached Kabul without being attacked.
There will be no Taliban incursion into Kabul from the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their insurmountable advance from 1994 to 1996.
At the time, Kabul was empty, the country was in flames and blood because of factional fighting.
Their takeover of the country was then seen as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants, in which they have been outmaneuvered by Al Qaeda, but their situation has not improved today.
The former mujahedeen, the Afghan government, and the current Taliban are united in their desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main characters of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have become traffickers, seizing public land to resell for development to returnees from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of huge American subcontracting contracts.
They are discredited; most of them, by the way, have not even fought.
People, I have heard in the countryside, want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, just as those who have been able to benefit from American largesse will leave: capital outflows are significant.
Young people are tired of war and its ideology.
