It is also imperative that Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports depend to a large extent, restore normal relations one day.
The withdrawal of French combat units was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional assistance: lycée for girls, boys, French faculty at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, in a bid to "win hearts and minds" and accomplish the impossible task of combining aid with offensive operations, the "civil-military activity" service of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), abolished in 2012, together with a small French NGO, has contributed to numerous public works and activities aimed at restoring agriculture in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, with the intensive involvement of local labor, were able to contain the rebellion: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection, and an increase in arable land.
What will we leave behind when we spend two billion euros on military spending?
A much more modest budget would improve the living conditions of the local population, which are very harsh in these valleys, often located more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The Embassy received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural work from local communities in Kapisa province.
To get rid of foreign-led uprisings, as farmers have told me, they need a small amount of non-military support that is well controlled and reaches them directly.
Egypt's Difficult Birth
This is another risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration that temporarily grants it emergency powers, it has decided to play it safe.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the following day.
Exactly one week ago, the Head of State gave the Assembly two additional months to finish its work.
Two years later, Egypt is relying on a provisional text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only deepened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic nonsense," continuing to "violate that word" and "flout the law."
His camp believes that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brothers to abandon their intention to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy while grievances rage across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote positively, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
All the more so because the call for an accelerated vote amounts to an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I reserve emergency powers," which are supposed to end with the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted in favor of the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not rise to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to communicate their views.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities, or civil society did the same.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 reserve members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, most of the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators were amused, incidentally, that one of the few disagreements of the day arose over... the time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the Constituent Assembly clock had been set incorrectly.
The text still being voted on yesterday consists of 234 articles.
The object of public attention, article 2, ultimately remained identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which states that "the principles of the Shariah are the main source of law."
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is a basic requirement, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules," which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," say the liberals, who see it as nothing more than a PR stunt.
Because, in their view, Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, because "the people called upon to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can see the emergence of theocracy. "
Many liberals are also aghast at the fact that the university's next chancellor is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no specific religious interference.
With this constitution, we remain within the ambit of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulemas, but university-educated people, some trained in the French system, "says Alexis Blouet, who is writing a thesis on Egypt's constitutional transition.
But he admits that "there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used in it are derived from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to fiqh [Islamic jurisprudence - editor's note].
And the question may arise in the future as to whether civilian judges are competent to rule on this. "
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they are significantly smaller than they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defense budget will take place not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter have also expressed concern about the text, which they consider to be detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy is still punishable and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
Moreover, no longer does any of the articles refer to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive development is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the poop of the Earth and the sea from brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort, and primacy of nature.
AiF has identified five of the most important reasons to visit Israel.
Let us worship the holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that God's grace is bestowed on all who enter this "font."
And Galilee is the place of Jesus "miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm, and filling the nets.
Here Jesus also appeared before his disciples after the resurrection.
But most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Way of Tribulation or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - the Praetorium - where judgment took place, and leads through the streets of the Old City to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha - the place of the crucifixion, the Stone of the Anointing, and the place of Jesus "burial.
There is also the symbolic Christian Poop of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem is erected on the site where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for Jews - the Wailing Wall, a remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes here with their wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a Vertical Trip
The ruins of the Massada fortress are the remnants of the secret refuge from enemies that Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on steep cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are keen on mountaineering can reach them on their own.
The rest are taken to this historic peak by a cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort of Hermon, where there is a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
It is reached by a shuttle bus from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of ski slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You won't be able to visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It holds the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean desert, and some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
It is also worth a visit to the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
His exhibition features works by Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acre, you can visit the Al Basha Baths Museum, which is a few rooms of ancient Turkish baths with models of visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops.
Entry is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most dramatic chapters in history.
The most tragic section, a children's memorial, was built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go into it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is mentioned there, too.
Wellness
Israel's three main resort areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red, and Dead Seas.
Each has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea bathes even in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not drop below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathes all year round.
By the way, this most extraordinary sea in the world is located at the lowest point on the planet - 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is brine, which easily keeps afloat even those who do not know how to swim at all.
The scenery around them is unrealistically beautiful.
They come here to undergo a course of treatment with salt water - rapa, and medicinal muds, and to treat dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to clean up damaged nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved in the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
The famous Sea Route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beauty Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say, if you touch the walls in the street of "your" sign, Fortune will be kind.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for photo shoots.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander around the Roman theatre and "capture" the Crusader fortress.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
To the Tourist on the Note
When going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English: about 30% of the country's population speaks Russian.
It is better to take money on a trip in dollars rather than euros, which can easily be exchanged for shekels (currently $1 = 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram, and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, with six stops connecting the Lower City to the Upper City.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
All forms of public transport cost 6 shekels, for which it is possible to travel with transfers within 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, Sabbath is celebrated in Israel.
Markets, shops, and public transport are closed from Friday evening until sunset on Saturday.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels offer only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that combine milk with meat.
There is a wide selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus paste, various sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of fattened cats that walk around on their own.
In the evening, they can even be seen sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Murlyks love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And it costs 15 shekels per day to rent a bike.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
In the Language of Numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine were the most likely to travel and have a rest.
From January to October 2012, 118,800 Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
The "Great and Powerful" will bring to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While deputies and human rights activists argue that the law on mandatory language testing will give, the country has already seen fraudsters selling "fake" certificates
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their sole purpose is to earn money to support the families left behind.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every migrant worker will be obliged to pass an examination on knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and communal services, household and retail trade.
However, over time, the FMS promises, the tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
Moreover, we will have to pass not only the language, but also Russian history and the fundamentals of legislation.
Language proficiency will have to be confirmed in order to obtain and renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
People who managed to obtain certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also not subject to the law.
Usefulness, Doomsday, and Protection of Rights
The network of examination points will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, Peoples "Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to pass the tests in all cities; already, more than 160 such centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce testing was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But human rights activists, before the law came into force, had time to ask the question in the press many times: what, in fact, will it yield?
What will change the obligatory knowledge of the language for both Russians and visitors?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service answer, it will reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery."
A lot of people are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Head of the Representative Office of the Federal Migration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment system can solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a profession or education, who do not know the language, who do not have a medical certificate, have problems.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev is convinced, a future migrant is doomed to encounter unscrupulous people who, under the guise of assistance, will thrust a "pass" into his eerie cramped barracks, where he and dozens of others like him will languish for months without food and documents, whipping up 12-14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, they are promised one thing, and upon arrival they are deceived, their passports are confiscated, and their promised wages are not paid," confirms Tolib Sharipov, Head of the Main Directorate of Labor Migration of the Migration Service of Tajikistan.
Don't swear, scoundrel!
Nevertheless, so far, many citizens of Central Asian republics who are going to work in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they aspire, but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, and Tajiks can afford even a basic education.
After all, their families have nothing to feed their children, let alone dress, dress, and equip them properly for school.
Growing up to adolescence, such children go to work at the first opportunity.
It's hard if you don't know the language well, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the language law, human rights activists point out one important point.
Testing will be carried out only for those migrants who have legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no examination and no formal follow-up work.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers are still living in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or No Unauthorized Entry"
Many of the visitors claim that it is not so easy to obtain official status in our country.
The reason is bureaucratic red tape and the same linguistic difficulties.
Besides, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand roubles.
But a fake registration can be done quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we mainly have false documents, no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Umed Khushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, shared with journalists.
"Fly, do not skimp, buy painting"
On the first day of the Language Law's entry into force, it became clear that it was not only migrant registration documents that were forged.
Several "fake" certificates of language tests have already been seized by FMS officers.
Counterfeit papers are printed on a standard colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them: each of the migrants, hoping to make it easier for themselves to pass the tests, paid seven thousand roubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official testing procedure, which will cost a migrant worker three thousand.
Both government officials and human rights activists agree that the main task in the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that "crusts" cannot simply be bought.
In the meantime, the authorities can promise migrant workers who fail the test the first time, time to study a basic language course.
In addition, visitors who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs does not take up the illegal arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is extremely low
The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia proposes to toughen the law against owners of civilian weapons.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: press shots at weddings, when there were no victims, and the massacre organized by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, as a result of which seven people were killed.
Police want to ban the carrying of weapons in public places and raise the age at which one can obtain a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, and promised that amendments to the law on weapons would be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy that the Russian authorities are trying to combat the problem by "tightening the screws."
An open letter appeared online, the authors of which - representatives of various public shooting organizations - demand to abandon the "senseless toughening."
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, criminal lawyer Vasily Lesnikov told the BBC Russian Service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of Internal Affairs, 142 crimes involving the use of firearms registered with the internal affairs agencies were committed in the first six months of 2012, while 1,168,000 crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter believe that stricter legislation in the field of civilian weapons will not prevent the criminal from going to the "black" market.
Now, according to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry claims that it is controlling the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The "black" arms market is replenished through several channels.
There are five main such channels, says retired colonel Viktor Baranets, who has worked for ten years in the structure of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of the site that accepts orders for weapons
The first is the "army or military footprint," that is, weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"Both Russian officers and Caucasians dragged the weapons," Baranets says.
The next type of "black weapon" is stolen by criminals from representatives of law enforcement agencies.
Baranets explains that this includes both those taken from police warehouses and those stolen from law enforcement officers themselves.
Illegal "guns" are being sold from military warehouses.
Explosions were frequent in many military warehouses.
"There are proven theories that some of the fires were deliberately set to cover up the shortfall," the former soldier said.
According to Baranets, the producers of weapons make their contribution.
"Now there are private arms factories that do not withstand competition on the international market and throw weapons from under the floor to the black market, including in Moscow," the expert says.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
Particularly from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan, guns and machine guns come in abundance.
"It has its own production, sometimes artisanal, and a mafia has formed, which organized the flow," the former soldier explains.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the sources of supply of illegal weapons to the "black" market.
A report on this in 2011 was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Management Design.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminological literature, and open data from portals on weapons-related topics.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers write, come from the military and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market ended up there "because of weapons-related officials," the report said.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of armed conflict, 14% are stolen during the production of weapons, and 5% are "black archaeology."
A sales consultant at one of the gun stores, who asked not to be named, claims that the weapons found by the black diggers are too old.
More often than not, he says, sellers go to a military warehouse for a new batch.
A warrant officer buys a unit, such as a TT pistol.
They prescribe it to him, they pass it through the fence.
"He takes it to the city and sells it for 900 euros a piece with two shops," he says.
"True, the police are aware of all the cases, so periodically, when the crime detection plan is on fire, they carry out a test purchase from illegal arms dealers," adds the consultant.
"Like in a luxury store"
Seller and buyer often find each other through acquaintances.
I looked at sites, blogs, until a friend responded, offering to come to Begovaya platform, where there will be a man who will take me to a "corner" where we will bargain.
I only found out the price of the barrel there
military columnist Viktor Baranets
To get the barrel, I need an acquaintance who has a way out, says the sales consultant. - I have such an acquaintance, but I am not sure about it.
There are sellers in the markets, but you also need to come there, conditionally, "from Ivan Ivanovich, who asked to be told that his daughter's tooth had fallen out."
Now I even get a couple of knuckledusters through someone I'm sure of.
He also supplies them only to me, because he knows that I will not surrender them.
Newcomers look for weapons in different ways.
Former military man Viktor Baranets tried his hand as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s, when he was preparing to publish an article about it.
Schemes, he said, have not changed.
He was given an album of photographs that contained "anything and everything."
"I felt like I was in a luxury store," recalls the military man.
The buyer, according to Baranets, is not offered a cat in a bag - everything is possible to try.
I, a potential customer, do not just buy - we go to the forest with the seller, there we set a target.
"I am given the opportunity to shoot, and when I am convinced that the weapon is hitting well, we start bargaining," the expert describes the procedure.
Shop on the sofa
Internet search engines lead to sites and groups in Vkontakte, where they offer to buy weapons "for different purposes."
No documents or face-to-face meetings are required.
"It is enough to have a certain amount of money," write the advertisement cap on the website "Buy a military pistol or an assault rifle."
