"So far, deceiving the brain turns out to be average"
The topic of augmented reality, which is popular among fans of modern technologies, has lately been perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
First, Google showed the operating model at its annual conference in the summer, and then in November it became known that Microsoft had also filed a patent application.
However, it follows from a conversation with Sharam Izadi, Head of the Interactive 3D Technologies Group at the Cambridge laboratory of Microsoft, that glasses are a past stage for the company's scientists.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, creating virtual open spaces.
- Please tell us in general terms what your research group is doing?
- We are engaged in human-machine interaction, but we are also trying to push the boundaries of that interaction.
So far, humanity has largely stuck with pixels on a flat screen, sometimes poking their fingers at them.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is sold without Kinect, because everyone is interested in sign control.
- What else awaits us?
- Despite the fact that Kinect has moved the interaction to the physical level, a lot still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), but the output is not yet very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to let the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
To do this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to complement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with those wacky virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A popular thing, but is it being overestimated?
- It certainly cannot be called a panacea - there is a question of privacy, because one does not always want to inform others about one's actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interaction with computers are good, but each is in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, not large ones, but such stingy, short ones.
At the same time, the gestures were not captured by the device's camera, but by a wristband that recorded movements of bones and muscles.
It is still large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future lies in a mixed type of control, such as gesture + voice.
- What is it like?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this can of soda?
You will say and show at the same time.
- I usually just speak.
- Oh, it will be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human responses.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they give a good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If you talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- In principle, the current generation is something from which we can build in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get a megapixel 8 at 1000 k / s.
But it's not about the megapixels themselves, but about the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From the latter point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us - this adds work to the algorithm designers.
That is, it is necessary to remember not only about the resolution on the X and Y axis, but also about the Z.
Speed, the number of frames per second, is also very important.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the current 30 k / s is quite low, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond laboratory made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay - from 1 to 100 ms, with modern serial sensors closer to the second (60-100) value.
Not everyone understands how this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
In my work, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful, but it does not require touching, so that there are more frames per second.
- Do you not need to increase the number of cameras?
- Kinect now has three "cameras," one of which is actually an infrared emitter and the other a receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a normal visible range sensor.
It is not used to determine the depth of an object.
Potentially more cameras could solve the problem...
Or exacerbate it by increasing the required volume of payments.
It would be nice to create a flexible analogue to the Kinect, play with the curvature of the cameras and see how this will help in three-dimensional positioning.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that glasses are one of the most promising platforms in terms of everyday use of augmented reality technologies?
- Of course, it's not very convenient to walk around with your smartphone in your raised hands all the time, but here's what I think: the coolest option would be "transient" augmented reality, where, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection display, and elsewhere.
Glasses are a very personal device, this is their strength (only you can see private things), and at the same time their weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from "Iron Man," but also to a mere mortal.
There is one problem, often pointed out by critics of such an idea: no tactile feedback!
Hands feel nothing!
What are your group's responses to this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
For now, one of the interesting tricks is to use the second hand as a kind of background for the image.
It registers clicks perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at making these "images in the air" tangible - for example, the interference of several directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located gives a feeling, but so far it is very weak - as if you have been blown on your pads.
There are also wrist bracelets that affect the nerve endings in the fingers - another promising trend.
- Did you try to deceive the brain?
To make him think that he feels what he must feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge that will remain to be worked on for a long time - how to make a person who is physically in a very limited space believe that he is walking on an open, almost infinite path - and we are working on the concepts of treadmills (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms, and huge balloons.
While deceiving the brain turns out to be average, the work is still many years away.
That's what makes working on virtual reality so attractive to researchers - many things are in their infancy.
