Shimon Ornest: We want to accumulate positive energy at concerts
What do you think is the end of the world in less than a month?
This is just one of the many disturbing news stories that we humans come across so easily.
Together with The Tap Tap, we joke about it all the time and say that we are the only band in the world that can muster enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
Moreover, in December you are going to give absolutely unique three concerts against the end of the world.
Could you tell readers more about this?
This is a nationwide fund-raising event that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which is announced on December 21 at 11: 10 a.m.
The day before this event, on December 20 at 21: 00, three concerts will start simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end, roughly speaking, when the May calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, whose time zone is 12 hours earlier than ours.
Who came up with the idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we came up with everything together with our artist Gonza Augusta.
Not only do we want to accumulate enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state of the world we will one day pass on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the May calendar, we have created a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world.
The Tap Tap band, together with other musicians, also performed an anthem against the end of the world called "The end of the world is cancelled."
Will the already popular YouTube anthem be played at these benefit concerts?
Of course, at the end of the day, if everything works out and the end of the world does not come.
It will be sung by all the performers at all the concerts at the same time.
At the same time, the anthems will also be played live on Czech television.
The lyrics to this song were written and played by the part of Jesus in the video by Tomasz Hanak, who also performs with Xindl X...
How did you begin to cooperate with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities in Czech cultural life, as we hold many charity events and concerts.
We try to actively involve them in these projects.
It turned out that many people like to work with us, they are interested.
What will the proceeds from the concert against the end of the world go to?
For the purchase of equipment for the STUDEO Accessible Education Centre, we have been working with the Tap Civic Association at the Jedlicka Institute for the sixth year already.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedlicka Institute and hold fun and interesting events with them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to their teachers, and we try to provide them with this opportunity in this way.
Within the framework of the Jedlicka Institute Complementary Construction Project, a separate building will be created in the future to which we will move with this project.
Several bands and performers will perform at each concert.
What were the selection criteria?
We tried to create a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marian Bango and Jiri Suchy will perform in Prague.
For more information, visit www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any such "grand events" in the future?
In May, we will be performing for the first time at the Prague Spring festival, and here, of course, we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year, we would love to perform at the Czech National House in New York, and personally, if we are in the United States, I would very much like to perform in Washington and Chicago.
You have serious plans for abroad; you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the road from the point of view of organization and logistics??
It's not as scary as it first appears.
We have five participants in electric wheelchairs, their wheelchairs must travel in the luggage compartment, plus a lot of cargo and tool cases.
Nevertheless, so far we have been able to cope without problems. Czech airlines CSA and British Airways have always been perfectly prepared for us, which has surprised me on so many occasions.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have you faced so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London, and other countries where everything works better than ours, we have seen in Russia that the East is still at a basic level.
Compared to Prague, there are many barriers in Moscow, and it is still unusual for a person in an electric wheelchair to move around the city centre on his or her own.
There are also no such banal things as giving way to a disabled person in an elevator.
Fortunately, there, too, public organizations are already emerging that are trying to draw people's attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
Where, on the contrary, do we constantly need to catch up with the advanced countries?
There are a lot of things that are far behind.
But it is important to make clear that improving and improving the situation always depends on the efforts of the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite normal for people with severe disabilities to move around on their own in the streets, to go to the toilet, to the museum, or wherever...
It is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities take an active part in public life, in this respect we with The Tap Tap are a little ahead of them!
Respect for the public or accessibility is one thing, but the moment we have famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians, or lawyers among us, things will really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases - people with a strong will.
The Tap Tap band is very popular nowadays, but let's go back two years, what made you start it in 1998?
I entered the Jedlicka Institute as a tutor, and there were a lot of young people around me who wanted to do something.
Since I am a musician myself and also play saxophone, I and a colleague organized an interesting music club.
Well, and over time, as our presenter Ladya Angelovic says, it got a little out of control (laughs).
Popularity has only come about in recent years, or am I confusing something?
It's true, we were helped by the fact that we started joining famous singers and working actively to promote the band.
We have come to the conclusion that work that no one can appreciate is essentially as if it does not exist.
Thanks to European Union funds, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment, and so on.
Was your goal to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the beginning, I felt their potential to do something extraordinary.
Show business is full of things that mimic one another.
It is logical, everything new is taken with care, and it lasts a long time.
There are very few rare things, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of the person who sees us is, of course, pity, it is natural...
But this pity is entirely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not some suffering and abandoned person we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live full lives and develop, of course, only if they have the necessary resources.
I say that if people with disabilities succeed, it is a shift not only for them, but for society as a whole.
Did you succeed because you were a tough leader, as many people think you are?
