Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began its close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and, in the years since, has actively participated in a number of the agency's projects.
But Poland's journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who, on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience indifferent, and after a few years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esso-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for "An Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was recognized, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway track equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea is unknown, as are the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to accelerate or brake the trolley.
Information about this tree is known only from the press of that era.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The research was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the preserved materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work "Air Torpedo Rocket and Airborne Bomb Rocket" by Leliwa-Kryblocki was published.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war itself, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) coordinated all projects for the military use of missiles.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, its work was terminated by the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautics Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, which published four long articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotowicz proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the POA became a full member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), the first chairman of the Astronautical Association, became Deputy Chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has contributed significantly to the development of the highly successful RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of traveling a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were conducted in the summer of 1959 at the Bledovskoye wasteland.
The missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could travel 14.5 km, and its mission was to observe high-altitude winds.
But in 1962, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM rockets was Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B, and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1S 0.62 liters.
All three types had a maximum range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the development of the Meteor-2 rocket took place at the Aeronautical Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a launch weight of 380 kg, was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, under the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Germaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
