In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution to the US, which had been his regime's patron for decades.
For the US administration, a positive outcome was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it would fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
But it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days, following negotiations brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate triggered a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
Defeat in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with Ronald Reagan's election.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo," chronicles an episode in that story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the embassy was occupied, six employees managed to escape.
After a difficult time, they finished their journey to the Canadian Embassy residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, aided by an extravagant cover story, according to which they left on Canadian passports as members of a film crew looking for a location in the country to shoot a sci-fi epic.
Combining genres
The plan, devised by "evacuation" expert Tony Mendez, required the cooperation of Hollywood.
For the legend to be true, specialized magazines wrote about the film project, organized press conferences, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have long been kept secret, with the film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-opus," a story of a successful venture, a scam - for example, a series of films about Ocean's friends.
The mood in the film is constantly changing - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were depicted in the film - there is no great difference in this).
On the other hand, there are lighter Hollywood passages that intersect with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from CIA headquarters and other agencies - men in suits discussing the situation at negotiating tables, on agency staircases, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has had a wonderful career relaunch.
From being ridiculed, the actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
At the same time, this is Affleck's first film, which is not being shot in the director's hometown of Boston.
A sense of place, however, is among the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in "Argo," where Teheran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the embassy's fall are impressive in their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseeability that arise when history suddenly changes somewhere.
Affleck and his co-stars achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in a Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works pretty well with that little bit, sometimes making things up - it all comes out not so elegantly (a scene in which a phone call in America averts a looming crisis at Tehran airport and a chase on the runway look rather far-fetched).
The downside of "Argo" is the dispersion associated with having to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as their Hollywood counterparts are indeed very charming, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a film that can be watched with moderate interest, assessing the staging and retro style that recreates the thrillers of the 1970s.
But it's hard to take.
But it is enough to remind us of one, still in a sense, living story, and to show how exaggerated perceptions of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com portal, which conducts an annual survey of the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop."
"We were prompted by the latest development, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40% quota for women in the administration of major European companies," Patrick Nager, the survey's organiser, told Pravo.
Among the absurdities already nominated is the recent decision by the European Court of Justice to combine the premium rate for men and women.
Until now, women have benefited from life insurance because they are objectively less at risk for insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be submitted to the competition by the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013, "said Nager.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of bio-components to fuels, which as a result harms nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain relatively small amounts of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of chicken cages, which has caused egg prices to rise significantly this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term "sandwich oil" or the withdrawal of classic light bulbs from sale was also criticized.
High-quality bananas should be 14 centimetres long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under pressure from one or another trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now even defends the demands of its banks under threat of the wind).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show an "abnormal curvature."
At the same time, the European Commission justified itself on the grounds that it was only harmonizing existing fragmented national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite opposition from some states, has relaxed standards for fruit and vegetables, arguing that the existing directives will lead to wastage of products.
A candidate to win the poll could be last year's EU regulation, which requires that balloons on sale must be accompanied by a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has turned to American studies that suggest that balloons while playing are a potential cause of death by asphyxiation in children.
A similar restriction now applies to children under the age of 14, who are prohibited from blowing into market stalls.
Funny ideas are born at home, too
The rule concerning European officials themselves is also absurd: anyone with an official position in the EU cannot, given the sensitivity of the subject for Greece, use the name Macedonia, but should instead refer to "FYROM" (The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
Bankovnípoplatky.com, in collaboration with Laissez Faire, an association of liberal economists, has proposed for a vote, in addition to the above-mentioned absurd rules, an EU regulation on the size of food reserves within a member state.
The EU has set the maximum amount of foodstuffs that can be stored in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the EU.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volume of canned mushrooms, for which it faced a heavy fine.
The questionnaire's organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and in the idea of providing subsidies for applications for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not Brussels.
"We are at a disadvantage because we don't have the sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation, "then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palace (CSDP) declared in the autumn of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high grain harvest, and as a result of so-called interventionist purchases, the state had full warehouses of stocks that had to be taken out.
Because the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to the Palace, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission reached out to the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
The Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Nemec (US-DEU), offered subsidies to villages, including for the preparation of an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations in member states are easily criticized, the EU's efforts to regulate and to improve the functioning and development of the EU are, according to many experts, more deserving of recognition.
A serious problem, according to experts, is drawing EU subsidies for projects that have not even a hint of anything to do with deepening European integration, but that member states have achieved in the budget negotiations.
It is also a source of emotion among Czechs that, as in other EU countries, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to a specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, retained the name "Olomouc cheeses," our producers had to rename "Tuzemak," whose traditions in our country date back to the 19th century.
Only products from cane distillate, not sugar beet, can be called rum.
In addition to the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from German Lübeck or Parma ham, the official list of registered EU products already includes, for example, Karlovy Vary rusks, Pohorzelice and Trebonski carp and Zatec hops.
Pardubice carrots and Gorzice pipes can also be proud of the EU trademark.
People want me to protect the republic, but I'm an amateur, "Okamura said.
Mr. Senator, how does it occur to a person to run for president?
I am not thinking about becoming a senator or president myself.
If everything functioned smoothly in our country, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can no longer watch the country being plundered over the past 20 years, thieves hustling around, people raising their taxes and the retirement age.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something that I don't like, I try to find a solution to change it.
And because I am in my forties and an independent with no party affiliation, I have no choice but to run for senator or president.
You made it to the Senate, but soon went to the presidential castle.
Are you turning your back on the people who elected you in this way?
I have said all along that I will enter the race for the presidency depending on the outcome of the Senate election.
Later, I specified that if I was elected a senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not a post; a post is a tool with which I can implement my views.
So I need the greatest influence and the broadest powers.
But the difficulty is not just that, as a nation, we grumble in front of our bars or the TV, but that we are prepared to trample on anyone who tries to change something.
Then there is the media, which denigrates people and confuse freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, it was said that I paid bribes to journalists, or that I was an adviser to Jiri Paroubek.
Let's move on to your views.
You started the fight for the presidential castle with theses about the material and criminal responsibility of politicians and about the return of property declarations worth more than twenty million.
To achieve this, the law must be changed.
As president, you have no such authority, and only the entire Senate can propose legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When I lobbied as a citizen to make tours a free enterprise, it was pushed through.
The problem is politicking - when someone comes with a good offer from the left or the right, they are deliberately obstructed, and this holds back citizens.
As an independent, non-partisan person, I have a much greater potential to gain support from all parliamentary parties.
My advantage is that I can take from every party what is best for our country, and apply it, without putting it on the shelf, without looking at dogma.
Do you see yourself as more of a right-wing or left-wing person?
From the Czech point of view, it seems to me that people regard me more as a leftist.
For me, it doesn't really matter whether it's a little left or a little right.
It is important to me that we move forward.
It's not about who is on the right and who is on the left, I want to bring people together.
I will always support any good solution for society, whether proposed by the HRCM or the ODS, and I will likewise oppose a bad idea.
You get angry when someone says you're a populist.
But don't you prove it with what you said?
When you create a business plan for a firm, you also have some ideal goals and views.
And that's what you're trying to get close to.
You can call it populism, but all the proposals I am talking about are already functioning in the world, or are being talked about by eminent experts.
But without the support of parliament, you will be left with only slogans.
And you won't last long in politics with that.
Or do you think that when you go out to people and talk to them, you will be able to exercise criminal and material responsibility?
I have no other option.
Only convince politicians, journalists, and the public, and try to lure them to our side, so that we get our way.
If I were elected President, it would not be a problem to organize a live television broadcast in which I would appeal to the presidents of parliamentary parties to legalize material and criminal responsibility for politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
And if they refuse, they will have to explain why they do not want to do so.
If there is a strong personality who speaks out about abuses, then pressure can be brought to bear on the political scene.
Take the direct election of the president - it was a result of public pressure.
I say outright that I am an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies to defend my beliefs and views.
I am just starting out in politics and I will try to get majority support for my agenda.
I try to promote things on my own; if that fails, I will finish in six years and return to the private sector.
It sounds, in part, as if Okamura should save the Czech Republic.
I am no saviour.
I know that I alone won't do anything, so I've bypassed a number of famous people to run for the Senate.
I went to Radim Yanchura, who refused because of the volume of work.
I also at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencova, who uncovered fraud with light fuel oil products.
I put myself forward because people are really dissatisfied, but now I feel like I'm in the balance.
Sixty percent of people did not go to the polls, and most of those who did chose representatives of the establishment.
There are only two of us independents in the Senate.
People have elected the Senate in a way that changes will be difficult to implement.
Despite this, I will fight for my views, for example, for the direct election of mayors and governors.
Are you thinking about founding your own party?
I haven't thought about it yet, because I don't have time to check the purity of every potential supporter's background, and I don't have the money to do it.
There is no money for the presidential campaign either, my transparent account has only twenty thousand CZK.
Do you have no money?
You are talking about property declarations, but what about your own affairs with this?
Personal assets are estimated at around 60 million.
I have a plot in Prague worth about 25 million, an apartment worth 10 million, another apartment worth 8 million, an art collection worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Skoda Superb worth a million, and a few million more in my account.
I got an Aston Martin, by the way, because it was my boyhood dream - I always liked James Bond, who drove a car, was gallant with women, and at the same time fought against meanness and lawlessness.
Do you drive an Aston Martin, own a £60 million property and have no money for a campaign?
You say that you want to change the republic, but you don't want to put your own money into it.
This is not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for a campaign.
Should I get into debt?
I have already put 2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors shows that my program is not that interesting.
And I am not obliged to pay for an election campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign costs will essentially be covered by my Senate salary.
But I wouldn't live on that money, for example, I wouldn't be able to pay my son for an English school that costs $30,000 a month.
If I only wanted to make money, I wouldn't be running.
So, will you continue to be an entrepreneur so that you can live?
Did you not say that you would reduce these activities?
But this does not depend on the size of the salary.
As I promised, I have reduced my activities in part.
For example, my deputy will become managing director of a travel agency in the spring.
People would like me to be an imperial guardian of the republic.
But I also have to live on something.
How much, as an entrepreneur, are you used to receiving monthly?
Two hundred to four hundred thousand, which I still get.
And if I were president, I would finish my business.
