MVRDV architects prove that true adventure is not just about imagination - Spijkenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I find this building fun, it looks futuristic, and finally we can see something interesting again," says Lisette Verhaig as she passes by on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks so: "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPads, and e-books.
Nobody goes to such old-fashioned libraries voluntarily any more, right?
Spijkenisse, an unremarkable sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
In order to combat this unfortunate circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to build seven fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painstakingly painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this outreach initiative has been modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had only one opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Winy Maas of Rotterdam-based architecture firm MVRDV, a master of bold bar charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, approached the task with his usual composure and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
As the jury looked around in bewilderment and shrugged, a defiant Maas folded a pyramid in size out of his original gift and ended his speech defending his project with the words: "Dear townspeople!"
Here's my suggestion: "Book Mountain" in Spijkenisse, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain, worth €30 million, has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent apartment buildings and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the competition "The Best Library of the Netherlands 2012."
The project also participates in the Dutch National Wooden Structures Competition 2012.
Thus, a faceless suburb that once had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall whose white facades suggest a dairy plant has become richer in one modern piece of architecture.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse has the first public cultural building in the town's history.
A Long Road to the Book
First impression: a bookish Eldorado under a cheese hood.
There is only one elevator in the middle of the mountain range, because true lovers of architecture and reading will prefer to explore the area on foot.
The glazed room from all sides is bright and easy to see, the floors of burnt brick and the elegant street lamps unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The gaze is involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Normally, bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic space configuration upside down and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the Book Mountain is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and technical rooms.
Particularly pleasing are the black bookshelves, which serve as wall finishing, parapets, or stairwell railings.
Their appearance, texture, and smell are unusual.
Even seasoned architects and civil engineers are lost in guessing what the unknown material is.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Traborst, the project manager representing the Spijkenisse community, as required by the standard.
And one day, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we came across a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, millimetre-thick artificial fibres have been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a root lining.
This is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles last for one or two seasons, after which they can be thrown away.
For the library, the cloth - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into panels four centimetres thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells a little like a new car and a little like a pair of sneakers.
105 steps lead to the top.
Whoever makes the 500-metre journey will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the right humidity on the literary mountain.
The Costs of a New Soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite a lot of glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Troborst.
Earth's heat is used to heat and cool it.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass cap, even on clear days, the sun does not get inside for long.
Wide laminated wood farms perpendicular to the glass facade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roll blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig has been here before, too.
And traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogard, who called Bukenberg "Spijkenisse's soul that has long been missed."
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to fill the empty shelves of the not yet fully staffed library, which had 70,000 books at the time.
The idea worked.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident is now connected to this new house in some way.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it serves only for decoration.
In this way, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Spijkenisse wrote his own literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
It is, after all, only a starting point for identity-building.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on recognition of Palestine.
In doing so, Berlin is balancing a narrow diplomatic path, according to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the Palestinians "application for observer status at the United Nations.
But Berlin then abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But, at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO carried out the proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, moving from a US-led policy, so to speak, to German foreign policy itself.
Complicating matters further, Europeans lack a coherent common policy.
Thus, the Germans are once again caught between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that for now they are just figuring out their role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as that pursued by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a position in its national interest that is independent of that of the US or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties to certain regions, such as Russia, China, or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend public opinion and elites in Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a part.
But I wouldn't place too much emphasis on it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the Germans "calculations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the US, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a fracture as the Libya issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
Opinions differ in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The US, by contrast, has made clear its support for the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European states?
Because of American domestic politics, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But, given the local political situation, the government cannot, of course, take such a position openly.
I believe that the significant differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem to be.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all enthused by Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand, and its position as the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that is what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, coherent European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot speak from a broader perspective and must instead act on the basis of their own vision.
That is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in forging a common European position.
Understandably, this is not easy for Germany, if only because of its ties to Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really assume a leading role?
Or is the lead still being given to Germany?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, still finds it difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany assumes an important role, a variety of anti-German sentiments manifest themselves.
It is not easy for the Germans to cope with this.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse position than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is steadily diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling that vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, dislike it, or hate it even more - that's life!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute that brings together academics and policy experts from Europe and North America to explore the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, Polo Ralph Lauren is, too.
But what is Armani Polo?
It is an officially registered name in China that has nothing to do with the firms from whose names it is derived.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
Even then, it is unclear whether they will be able to assert their rights.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specialises in trademark infringements in the Far East.
Every week, a new case of this kind comes to my desk.
Simulators need only add a couple of letters to be eligible to register their trademarks.
So Gucci turns out to be Lu-Gucci, Prada-Kny can be registered instead of Prada.
German companies, such as sports goods maker Puma, are being legally copied in the same way.
Pattloch opens a folder with the records of the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered there the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also uses the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property rights.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey department stores selling almost exclusively counterfeit goods.
However, Pattloch's case is different. On behalf of his clients, he opposes Chinese enterprises receiving from the trademark registrar the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Ban Mingpai," a brand-name passenger.
The word is associated with "Ban Dakuan."
This is the name given to women who prey on rich men.
Chinese authorities plead not guilty
"It's damaging to business, it needs to be addressed," Pattloch said.
"The brand is being eroded, a unique position is being lost, the image is badly damaged."
Financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries run into the millions, especially in the case of expensive copyrighted products.
According to market research firm CLSA, with sales of €15 billion a year, China is the third-largest and fastest-growing market for luxury goods.
However, deleting dubious entries in the trademark registry is difficult and costly.
The process can last up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch recounts cases in which the court dismissed claims because, after a long time, the contested name became a "market reality."
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarist because he damaged his trademark in China, Pattloch said.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also the famous cases of graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that had recently acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
Therefore, the Chinese still have the right to use an emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
The company that bought Volvo, Geely, originally used a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, and Geely had to change it.
Fashion manufacturer Lacoste lost out in China to imitators in Hong Kong and Singapore, where the famous crocodile looked the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not consider themselves to be at fault.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 due to a shortage of staff and equipment.
But last year, there was a "return to normality from an emergency in the work process."
For example, the backlog of objection cases has fallen by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases have been closed, a 75 percent increase from last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending before the agency.
Fighting it is expensive
As is so often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China topped the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth time in a row, the agency reports.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were paid.
Simplified, this means that each registration costs, on average, 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
