Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and tripper (gonorrhea).
Frequent viral STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (a fungus), gonorrhea, and the human papilloma virus.
HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults is relatively low - but about 20 percent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are significantly more common than among other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
We also have a high incidence of human papilloma virus among young people.
How is the number of infections changing?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
The incidence of syphilis has more than doubled, from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, urinary complaints, discharge, lower abdominal pain, and blisters or lumps.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
After all, some of the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread through contact infection and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular screening, especially in the case of frequent changes in sexual partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid long-term consequences.
