But it is the southernmost part of Azerbaijan, and the Iranian border is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the Talysh, one of the peoples of the Caucasus, about whom not much is known, except that they speak excellent Farsi and Azerbaijani and are distinguished by their longevity.
The final destination is Lerik.
The small town boasts too heavy architecture of Soviet times, which does not at all harmonize with the picturesque mountain landscape.
Tourists from Europe hardly come here, the road from the Azerbaijani capital Baku is too tiring.
The 323-kilometer journey takes eight hours, as the road has only one lane.
The legendary wealth to which the country owes the oil of the Caspian Sea has not yet arrived here in the province.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that there is something to interest tourists in Lerik.
"In May, Baku became famous for the Eurovision Song Contest - and next year we will have a festival of the world's oldest people," Fatulayeva says.
She is the director of the museum of longevity, probably the only one in the world.
Here the biography of about eight dozen Talysh people from these places, who are more than 100 years old, is documented. Fatulayeva points to a black and white photograph.
This is my grandfather, he is 120 years old here.
At the age of 136, he had another child
But the museum's controversial star is Shirali Muslyumov's shepherd, who is said to be 168 years old.
There is, however, no birth certificate.
And, given that the oldest documented person is 122 years old, Muslyumov's age seems extremely doubtful.
"He was born in this area in 1805, died in 1973," Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children, and allegedly had a daughter at the age of 136.
So has the shepherd Muslyumov added a couple of decades to his age?
After all, even Rembrandt Scholz, an age researcher at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has heard of centenarians in Central Asia.
"An astounding number of elderly people can also be found in parts of China, in Japan, or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," says Scholz, "Sardinia is also home to an extremely large number of very old people."
However, in the absence of documentation, scientific proof of age is impossible, as there were no civil registers.
A glass of melted butter every day
Nevertheless, there is a fact that people in the Lerik area are strikingly often of biblical age.
There are now 20 people over 100 years of age living here.
Why are there so many centenarians here in the south?
Azerbaijani tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains this by special Talysh genes.
Director of the Fatulayeva Museum, on the contrary, believes that it is all about nutrition.
Talysh people love meat, bread, and most of all dairy products, many of them drink a glass of melted butter every day. However, it is unlikely that such a high-calorie diet can be healthy from a nutritional point of view.
Or is it a primitive way of life that keeps people young? Rubaba Mirzoeva lives in Chengemiran, a tiny village near the city of Lerik.
At 97, she is still relatively young for these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor with a barrel of butter, which she rolls tirelessly back and forth.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and daughter, who have long since had grandchildren of their own.
There are also two toddlers jumping nearby.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared and served in typical bubbly glasses of armudu.
Mirzayeva has perfectly smooth and strong white teeth and hides long dark blond braids under her headscarf, which her son proudly reveals to us.
I always wash my hair with milk so it never falls out and retains colour.
"And I've never used shampoo," Mirzayeva says.
