People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist and extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning him by name, the attack is called "what happened on July 22."
Norwegians find it hard to believe that, in their peace-loving country, one of their fellow citizens is capable of such atrocities and killings.
At the heart of Norway's current prosperity is the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason for our prosperity," says Anna, our waitress carrying trays of seasoned rakfis, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic well-being.
We are the kind of people - as you call them - that are sensible.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We don't like to show off, we're not boastful.
Norway treats its oil very carefully - most of the oil and gas industry's revenues are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was throwing away money they didn't have, Norway was frugally calculating the costs.
"As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that's enough for happiness," says Anna.
"And there's rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm queuing in the snow for some food - I've had enough of it.
Here is a burger with elk meat - it is certainly exotic, tasty juicy meat.
But in the evening, more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell awaits us.
My hotel hosts a special rakfisk dinner, during which visitors vote on the best, or perhaps the most aromatic, fish.
There is a live television broadcast, which shows the presenter in a bow tie surrounded by plates of rakfis.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what rating did you give for the best fish there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment..."
Everyone is laughing and cheering.
Someone falls from a chair, possibly after getting over an aquavit.
Or maybe it's just the smell of that fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto faces a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico's newly elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, prepares to take office, the BBC's Will Grant takes a look at the challenges he will face and the mixed expectations of his country's population.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad right now.
The city is also congested at the best of times, and steel fences have been erected since Monday, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not to prevent people from commuting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from reaching the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will wear the presidential armband and take over the reins of the country.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has performed well economically under Felipe Calderón's outgoing administration, but the country is mired in a drug war that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government tells the people of Mexico that it is ready to fight violence," Mr. Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I intend to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve that goal.
Before such statements, Mr. Peña Nieto's political career developed alongside that of the US president as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the nation's capital, opinion on the new leader is divided.
The Straight Man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered fondly.
Residents credit him with reviving tourism, developing the resort sector, and creating infrastructure.
The city is reachable by one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new highways, which are strikingly different from the potholes and pits that were previously in place.
Plaques bearing his name hang on a modern sports centre building and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are pinning our hopes on him for real and serious change," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman for Peña Nieto's PRI-led Institutional Revolutionary Party.
We look forward to the real and decisive change that our country desperately needs, particularly in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 consecutive years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that, after a 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
Moreover, he refutes the opposition's accusations that the new president is devoid of substance.
He is very straightforward and very committed to his vision for the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different view of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, stands in stark contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under motorway flyovers, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in this megalopolis.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to quell drug gangs in these areas, and violence against women is particularly acute.
Dozens of bodies of murdered women have been found in wasteland near a vast landfill in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in the state of Mexico during Mr Peña Nieto's governorship - far more than in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juárez, which has become a household name when it comes to killing innocent women.
According to Mr. Peña Nieto's opponents, he has, at best, failed to address the problem of femicide during his tenure as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of turning a blind eye.
Irinea Buendia, a resident of a concrete house that resembles most of the houses in this run-down neighborhood, struggles to hold back tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner killed her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed," Ms. Buendia recalled.
There were signs that she had been beaten and her body was already dead.
Mariana's mother recounts the story, and a portrait of her daughter looks down at us from the wall where it hangs next to a crucifix inscribed with just one word: justice.
That, they say, was what the family was denied.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just accept what they say and keep quiet.
But it's wrong, it shouldn't be, especially when there are so many violations and flaws around, "she said.
By wearing the presidential armband on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will shoulder a heavy responsibility with her.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime over the past six years, and the new president has promised to make tackling the problem a priority during his tenure.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was as governor," said Olvera, a PRI congressman from Valle de Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain about mistreatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims of poor detention conditions.
The hearing focused on Manning's time at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is seeking to dismiss the case on the grounds that Manning's detention conditions were harsh.
A US Army private is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in US history, did not take advantage of multiple opportunities to file a complaint about the mistreatment he said he suffered while in a military prison.
Under cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing at Fort Meade, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Maj. Ashden Fein, said records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of mistreatment.
The cross-examination, as part of a defense motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that his conditions of confinement were harsh and in themselves sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning said he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was subsequently published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, Fein, along with Manning, reviewed reports that were filled out after administration officials visited Manning during his time at Quantico, where he was held under high-security confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked about the reports Friday, Manning acknowledged that he found the treatment by prison officials "excellent" and the overall conditions of confinement "very professional."
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of mistreatment, even though Manning was asked directly about his conditions of detention, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had expressed verbal concerns about the issues and that visiting administration officials had discussed them with him and said they would be addressed, but did not record them in writing.
"They wrote down" no problem "(after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the issue in the conversation," Manning said.
The military judge, Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a hearing of a commission examining suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning said that during that hearing he wanted to have his "injury prevention" status lifted and his conditions of confinement relaxed.
Military officials explained that the restricted confinement regime - a level lower than suicide prevention supervision - was introduced to protect the detainee as well as the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was fine, that they would repeal the injury prevention regime... that my standard of living would improve, from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he once lost consciousness because of the heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is being resolved and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
While at Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - alone.
Manning says he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down during the day was forbidden by the rules.
During his sleep, Manning said, he was constantly hit in the eye by light from outside his cell.
If guards didn't see his face when he rolled over in bed at night, he said, he was woken up and forced to roll over on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he made during Thursday's testimony that after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates for a morning check.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Under questioning from the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he had to drop a blanket that could have covered him, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning said Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could have used underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope the judge will at least take into account what he went through during his incarceration and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is convicted by a court-martial, which is due to begin early next year.
The defense has said it plans to ask Manning to plead guilty to lesser offenses and contest other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon says Manning was held at Quantico under rules governing maximum-security detainees.
Manning's charges include aiding the enemy, unlawfully facilitating the release of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defense, and stealing government property or documents.
If convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My crisis of national identity is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of a lack of opportunities for self-fulfillment.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control area, and stood still.
Signs pointed to two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called Mexican all my life.
It's just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italians.
Later, I focused on the complex construction of "Mexican-American."
But here I was in Mexico.
There was no need for conventional names or complex structures here in my grandfather's homeland.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than native speakers, and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took out my American passport and queued for Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago, when Mexico's newly elected President Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the familiar issues of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs, and trade.
President Peña Nieto has been eager to talk about the upturn in the Mexican economy, so that Mexicans can now, with equal success, stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and a North American trading bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto has promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals have been made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders at gunpoint to relinquish half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events everywhere.
So when a US statesman says nothing critical of Mexico, there are complaints in the press and among the elite of Mexican society that the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And Montezuma's descendants are belligerent.
Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the US is the most complex.
Want to talk about grievances?
There are enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in the country, and those who do not.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican origin for one reason only: at one point in their family history, someone - a father or grandfather - was unable to fulfill himself in Mexico and had to head north.
More often than not, they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark-skinned, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
Mexico sees it differently.
Today, our lives are the fulfillment of the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must not forget that even that dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
United States of America.
Moreover, we know that most of Mexico's elite and ruling class do not like us.
We respond in kind.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as unreal Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, having found a full life in the US, but having lost spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the US as a child, and it reminds me that there is some friction between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican-Americans resent it.
She is a US citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the US, we're called Mexicans.
Now, as I learned during my trip, as if our relationship is not already complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to re-establish relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to serve as ambassadors of sorts for Mexico and to represent its interests in the US.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could persuade political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
Nothing will come of it.
Too many wrongs in the past.
And, given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption, and drug trafficking, many of us don't think the country is that great at all.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And rightly so.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what it did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will also have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still offended by the way their relatives were treated in Mexico more recently.
Yes.
Perhaps we have more in common than I thought.
Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis possible in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed suggests that such hopes are futile.
There is a familiar, meaningless debate about who started it; scores of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from Gaza have landed in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their perennial conflict, change has arrived in the Middle East.
This may be different, but the events of the Arab Spring have swirled around a host of well-established realities, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been spared the whirlwind that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even bloodier than before.
But there are reasons for hope in breaking this mortal impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the cease-fire signed on November 21 holds, this week's clashes have only strengthened the position of security forces on both sides.
Leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in Gaza in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat, despite their losses.
Despite the destruction of some of the group's leaders and the blockade of 1.7 million residents in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas's leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
A resurgent regional leader, Turkey, once Israel's closest Muslim ally, has come out in support of Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Celebrating Hamas supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where the militant group Hezbollah rules, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels are on the verge of toppling Bashar al-Assad, and further to Jordan, where Hamas's allies threaten the king's rule.
The most significant shift in the region's balance of power has occurred on Israel's southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood has grown under President Mohamed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator with little regard for Hamas support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more populist.
In future diplomacy, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas was defeated.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost and successfully destroyed many of Hamas's rockets.
Israelis can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the US has stuck to its unchanged position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under Binyamin Netanyahu's government, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part because of the wall, which enters the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite being illegal under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in the run-up to the January 22 election - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under Avigdor Lieberman, is well positioned.
What is the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them a state of their own?
If they were to be given full authority in the West Bank, would they not launch rockets from there toward Israel, as their brethren in Gaza do?
Better to keep them behind a wall and stifle any attempt to raise their heads.
It is possible that the hardliners will prevail; but their calculations may be challenged by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings toward Israel, their priority will be domestic issues.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egypt's president, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the cease-fire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change takes hold in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a ticking time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas are paying the price for the international community's growing discontent.
Both sides need external impetus
There remains the only solution that sensible people on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, have relentlessly called for: the establishment of two states and the cession of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
The hope, not too impressive in the short term, is that a cease-fire will enable other countries to exert more effective influence over the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which has long since decided to cut off the flow of weapons into Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the 1967 borders of the Jewish state, with land swaps and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
That would do more to create a Palestinian state than an upcoming UN vote that could result in recognition of virtual statehood for Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he remains reluctant to get involved.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, standardized cigarette packaging legislation has come into force.
Smoking warnings and images of diseased body parts stand out in stark contrast on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia's world-first plain packaging law for cigarettes and tobacco products has come into force, replacing the logos and colours of different brands with the same box of dull olive green with eerie images of diseased body parts and images of children whose health has been damaged by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the various images and signs warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, which are mandatory from Saturday, are the names of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the world's harshest conditions for packaging tobacco products.
Australia's federal government says the measure is aimed at discouraging young people from smoking by stripping the habit of its fashionable status.
The decision was based on research showing that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 never become smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
"It is clear that even at a very young age, children understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging," said Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown, for example, that a crown in a logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia has one of the world's lowest smoking rates, so the changes will have little impact on multinational profits, but other countries are already considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has strenuously opposed the legislation.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and accessible cigarettes are sold.
"This legislation will have serious consequences that are different from those intended by its proponents," said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these goods for sale on Australia's streets.
For some, by contrast, the new laws help businesses grow.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd says demand for cigars and silicone cases that conceal unpleasant images on packaging has soared (almost from scratch) since companies such as British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris, and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in Australia's high court two months ago.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesalers and is waiting for a new batch.
It's good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures, according to experts, is the popularity of social media among the very segment of the population targeted by the measures.
After a series of laws in Australia outlawed television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events, and prohibited cigarette sellers from displaying cigarettes in public, tobacco advertising has moved online.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict overseas sites.
"If you are a tobacco trader and you have only this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online may seem very tempting," explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman has seen an increase in the number of reviews of brands written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social media sites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco's Australian arm says the industry is now more concerned with adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even gone as far as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims in the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, even though all of these countries have very little trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
Tanya Plibersek said the government had been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to make it mandatory to post photos warning of the dangers of smoking.
The rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Plenty of smokers in Australia are defiantly disobeying the changes.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
"You just grab a cigarette and put it in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a photograph of a mouth tumour on the pack.
Frankly, the only thing that might make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yoo, who runs the King of the Pack tobacco shop in central Sydney, says uniform packaging has made it harder to place products on shelves
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch; now it takes me four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and banned cigarettes completely, we would have said," OK, it's over, we're closing the shop, "" he says, throwing his hands up.
It's not all bad to be bored in a world of electronic networks and constant connections.
This Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical problem and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I will not deceive you.
A half-day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and there are no books, no magazines, no iPhones, not even duty-free shops.
Recently, however, a growing number of scholars and child development specialists have spoken out in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and our children to be bored.
This causes the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may encourage creativity.
And because we are all constantly in front of a screen in the modern world, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Perhaps we should aim for boredom?
Yes.
And yet no.
We'll come back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, argues Peter Tui, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"Boredom actually has a very ancient history," he says.
Latin inscriptions about boredom dating back to the first century are found on the walls of Pompeii.
That leaves open the question of how we understand boredom.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying research on the topic and asking a task force of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people "want but cannot do things that would satisfy them."
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that the bored person doesn't do what he wants to do.
With apathy, you don't want to do anything.
The key to boredom, he says, is "attention disturbance and the associated mood deterioration and feeling that time is running out slowly."
Boredom can be described as very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood argues that while there may be a link between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances around them, and depressed people see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when it's really hard to focus on something.
In their study, "The Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some of the participants also heard loud noises from an unrelated television program in the next room, others heard the same noises at a low level so that they could barely be discerned, and a third group listened only to a voice recording without an external soundtrack.
Those participants who heard low-level TV reported that they were bored, more often than not - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for it and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or fascinating task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, looking at the flow of products on a conveyor belt in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed, he continues, that when people begin to swing on a chair or draw scribbles on a piece of paper, they do so out of boredom, but we now know that actually doing so simply helps not to relax physically.
"Research has shown that children who are not prohibited from twisting and twisting learn better and memorize more information than children who are required to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all get bored: when a flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
Different people, however, show different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a "Boredom Scale" to measure these individual traits.
Questions and statements such as "Much of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I have too much interest, so I don't have time for anything" are used to determine the score on this scale.
Using such questionnaires, researchers found that boys are bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he used a pager to communicate with nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
It found that 32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing their homework, and 23% said they were bored outside school.
Meanwhile, only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar data on boredom would be like now, 21 years later.
But he knows that "adolescence is the peak of boredom," largely because children and teenagers are not allowed to decide what they want to do.
To return to my original question: Is boredom good?
Sometimes not, because, in extreme cases, studies show, it can encourage people to engage in absurd and dangerous physical activities, gamble or abuse certain substances in an effort to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the link between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"That's how our brains tell us to do something else; that's boredom," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But this same brain does not always know what is best to do.
If you get bored and channel that energy into playing guitar or cooking, you'll make yourself better.
However, if you watch TV, you will only be better off for a while, and soon it will be over.
So if your child is bored and you give them an iPad, they won't be bored, but they won't learn to fight boredom on their own or otherwise manage their time and activity, says Professor Fenske.
"And such self-regulation skills are used in a variety of situations," he argues.
Your child is not only learning to do something on his own; he is also learning to control himself in general.
I don't think boredom should be celebrated.
But it should not be regarded as a bad thing, either.
Rather, one must learn to feel comfortable even outside the constant flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"We see it in a way that we need to experience boredom more often, and boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful," he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from the constant worries and just relax.
"In today's world, we are used to constantly over-stimulating our senses," he says, "and when silence comes, we get lost and don't know what to do."
It's unclear how Colorado's new marijuana legalization law will be implemented
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old football player and community college student in southeast Colorado, is charged with a criminal offense that will soon be perfectly legal statewide: possession of a small portion of marijuana and the pipe in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orozco said that one day in September, he and friends were driving in Lamar on the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco was issued a summons for drug possession and possession of a drug paraphernalia - minor offenses that each carry a $100 fine - and a court date was set.
"We are treated like criminals," Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has persisted in the weeks since Colorado voted to legalize small amounts of recreational marijuana, the resolution of hundreds of minor cases depends less on the law than on the location of the case.
Charges of minor marijuana offenses have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has adopted a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped charging people 21 and older for low-dose possession, which will become legal as soon as the law takes effect in a couple of weeks.
In more conservative Colorado counties, however, prosecutors have decided to pursue existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute possession of the drug.
At the same time, some cities from the Denver suburbs to the mountains of the West are voting to keep new, state-licensed marijuana shops out of their neighborhoods.
"It's all moving so fast that I don't even know what to expect next," said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in Washington state are scratching their heads, too.
They will have to establish rules for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution, and sale of marijuana, all of which must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in regulating marijuana use, first for medical use and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so they will set a good example," said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcoholic Beverage Regulatory Board.
But now no one can do more, Mr Smith admits, than put forward some proposals and hope it works.
"We don't have a real precedent to follow," he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will take effect on December 6 and leave the state in limbo for a year, when the state's licensing system does not yet exist and possession of marijuana has already been legalized.
And there are still difficult technical issues to be resolved during this period, such as how to balance the state's order of "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on selling it within 1,000 feet of schools, parks, playgrounds, and day care centers.
"It will be particularly difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses within cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs," said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly created Center for Marijuana Legalization research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates of Police in Aurora sent an e-mail to his subordinates informing them that the city attorney's office would no longer prosecute anyone over the age of 21 for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that police would stop prosecuting people for such violations "from now on."
Chief Oates said police would enforce city rules governing medical marijuana growers and would pursue illegal drug dealers and distributors.
The prosecutor for Weld County in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, is taking a more rigorous approach to the issue.
After the vote on the bill, he said prosecutors would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, primarily to encourage users to seek treatment.
So far, 119 people have been charged with possession of two ounces or less of marijuana, though many face other charges.
"It is our agency's responsibility to prosecute actions that are deemed criminal at the time they are committed," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
Reaction has been mixed even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer prosecute adults for possession of small amounts of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop charges in the already pending marijuana possession cases.
"I believe that it is our direct responsibility to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, incorporating recreational marijuana into the state and legal system will not be easy.
And conflicting reactions from residents across the state have exposed the ambivalence of local authorities about the state's marijuana experiment.
"There is a cultural barrier for district attorneys on this issue," said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents those convicted of marijuana possession and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
"They've persecuted people for so long for this that they can't really accept that it's not a crime anymore," he said.
Colorado and Washington - the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana in the same way as alcohol - are destined to be pilot states to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Legalization advocates and state officials plan to expand legalized commerce, but they are wary of guidance from federal authorities, who still plan to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Supporters of marijuana legalization hope that the Justice Department will back down on the issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of medical marijuana dealers and patients, the federal government has mostly authorized medical marijuana sales in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Enforcement Agency agents are unlikely to break into homes to seize a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for federal authorities to act.
Even before the presidential election, some local governments approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana shops, which would not have opened until less than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, introduced a six-month ban on marijuana sales, which is likely to be approved next week.
"We don't want to be in a position where we license someone and then it causes serious problems at the federal level," said Bob Nicholson, a City Council member.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I was expelled from Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the world's best educational institution, the modern equivalent of an ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freedom of thought and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Worcester College, Oxford University, in the late eighties, I packed my bags and left, in what turned out to be the first real scandal of my life.
My father couldn't stand it and wept.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed I had dropped out of college because I didn't like my classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from chipped cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was bullied for one reason only, and in this celebrated cradle of enlightenment it seemed barbarism and blind bigotry: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a Conservative supporter myself.
So, you ask, why think about it now?
According to recent data, a new generation of center-right students is being subjected to the same kind of harassment.
Such is the institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of Conservative students at Oxford that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as those afforded to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwelcome" because of their political views.
They want to add a representative to the college's equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only made worse by a recent BBC 2 documentary on student politics, Wonderland: Young, Smart, and Right, which portrayed the Conservatives as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film showed Joe Cooke, the former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, riding in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a silver-plated walking stick.
At other universities, Conservative students complain that they are being made "scapegoats for higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing bias within the university community.
People who don't even know us consider us to be the arrogant and violent children of wealthy parents. "
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi College, where the petition for greater protection was filed, calls the atmosphere "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, says the attitude of members of the student club towards those with centre-right views has deteriorated significantly.
"This is a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual debate and the normal life of club members," she said.
In my first few weeks at Oxford, I was not just in the minority; I was alone.
I went there in September 1986, a shy and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was awash with hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to strip former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree because of budget cuts to higher education.
Even Stalinists would be uncomfortable in such an atmosphere.
In the early days of Freshers week, when students get to know each other and the faculty, I felt for the first time what lay ahead.
What I didn't know was that not only did teachers condone the bullying of Conservative students, but they were also happy to take part in it themselves.
Political issues - the miners "strike, privatization, and the government's opposition to sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa - permeated the wood-paneled walls of the classrooms.
At my first seminar, I had to translate an eighteenth-century French text into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was difficult for me to get through, I got stuck in.
Harry Pitt was a very bile man with a cake-like face.
"Are Thatcherites fundamentally not learning French, or are they just brainless?" he asked.
Other students giggled.
Tears came out of my eyes.
"I advise you to take some early French lessons in your spare time, unless you're very busy spinning around in the company," quipped Pitt.
I went back to my room utterly miserable.
That evening in college, I was sitting alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year English student who introduced himself as a member of the University Conservative Association.
"I know who you are," he said amiably.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
Anyone suspected of sympathising with the Conservatives will be mocked.
It's not easy for me, and in your case they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be harder for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour. "
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick failed.
A first-year student of philosophy, politics and economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: "You're the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious. '
Other students echoed his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex?" one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the decriminalisation of the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only in the middle of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour woman and hide my true beliefs?
The three years ahead of me began to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only lecturer at my college who made no secret of his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He barely showed up in college.
He despised it for its provincialism, pettiness, and adherence to a Marxist-deterministic view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents "home in London, seeking refuge among relatives and unbiased metropolitan friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the Forties, all political views were accepted there.
"But it's the best university in the world," he said.
- They are not capable of such a thing, but not in a city of dormant spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved impeccably. "
His wet eyes blurred.
"Don't make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You will break my heart if you drop out of university. "
I was exhausted by the constant trips to London and my emotional protection was weak.
My friend, also a Conservative, could not bear the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
The following week, at a seminar, when another history teacher called me "the enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Burning with shame, I confessed that "my parents brainwashed me" and called them "old fools."
The respite was short-lived.
The final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was my father's.
At the time, he was writing two columns a week for Rupert Murdoch-owned newspapers.
My door was locked.
I didn't leave, and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and boarded the first train to London.
I never came back.
Call me a weeping rag.
But at the age of eighteen, no one should be subjected to such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
It is all the more sad that this was Oxford, which not only produced fourteen Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
ABC talks to Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other well-known clients of the Italian designer about the Valentino: Master of Sewing exhibition, which opened this week in London
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
