"I love this palace," he says in his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "il signore" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
The first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, is replete with personal letters and photographs signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as the trophies of his social ascent, from the humble tailor from Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international "elite."
There is nothing wrong with being in love with the royal court.
"They don't even put out cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet, like some great pop stars do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an excellent host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad," explains "Heini" Thyssen's ex-wife, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
Yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza recalls the charismatic fashion designer.
One day, we went to dinner at his house, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style manifested itself in every detail of his apartment, in its decoration, in its food, in its music.
