The World's Hardest Occupation: Miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and limb by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others who literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulphur gas rising from the depths of the earth solidifies on contact with the air.
After breaking off huge pieces of sulphur, which can weigh up to 70 kg, he places them in two bamboo baskets, weighs them on his shoulders, and carries them up a steep, rocky road.
It is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 metres, but the exhausted loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb in tortoise-like steps, struggling to maintain their balance and carefully probing the road to avoid slipping and falling over the precipice.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the Kawah Ijen cliffs a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur they produce
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists, who photograph them as if they were monkeys from a circus, and, wearily carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company has placed just above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano and, better yet, its workers since 1960, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, because the mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Since it is the norm to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk," Anto, who usually carries three daily, explains to us.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While that seems a minuscule amount for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn on the field.
"Miners' daily wages are very high by local standards, where coffee harvesting is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not that heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a compelling reason that is as devastating as sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Hindu-dominated Bali and brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and has tears in his eyes because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking his life in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulphur had already begun to affect him despite wearing a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and has tears in his eyes because of the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
That is the price he must pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could have been a tour guide, waiter, or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because the sulphur does not stop leaking at night when its characteristic yellow colour turns blue and glows in the gloom.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting up the road with a small torch attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such hardship.
In fact, they do not receive even a fraction of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photography fee that, along with the 15,000 rupee (1.2 euros) admission fee, the conservancy charges tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"It's a job for cattle, not people," says Badrucin, a stocky porter for 42 years who has spent three decades on Kawah Ijen since leaving college.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilograms, he says he will tolerate work "as long as he can," because he needs money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life
Although sulphur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so resilient that no one complains about their severe illnesses... more serious obviously than their habitual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder sores, which have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms at 53 years of age.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulphur out of the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
"I won't retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, his mouth wide open, missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: what human mules from the Kawah Ijen do.
Singapore seeks children to save its economy
Singaporeans blame careers, stress, and housing and education costs for not having children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a patriot husband, you are my patriot wife, let's fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unlikely that these lines are part of an advert for mint tortillas, but despite this - or perhaps because of it - the video became a hit on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local proverbs like "Let's put the bao (bun) in the oven" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising agency that made the video, BBH, cherishes the hope that it will be able to draw attention to the problem in an entertaining way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do "their national duty."
It's an Internet-only thing, so we had to make it fun and funny.
This is the main problem in the country.
We are the worst in the world in terms of reproducing ourselves, so we felt that this was a topic that we needed to address.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things, like launching perfumes with pheromones or organising fast-dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they did not necessarily work.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible to solve this problem, namely compose a rap?
1.2 children
Who does not take this so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and provides tax credits.
But all of this has little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leadership and strict social control.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population office, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Couple and Family Policy Division of the National Population Directorate, says the reason is "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"This has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family," she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and the postponement of marriage and childbirth, which has reduced Singapore's birth rate.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy that aims to dramatically increase immigration to counter population decline is causing resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are Web sites where barely disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and refusing to integrate, thrives.
Rising immigration is also seen as one reason why Singapore's ruling party scored its worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem, with quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have a known impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health-care spending, and immigration policies, Singapore's example is also beginning to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is making an effort not to build so many small dwellings.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The Urban Development Guide has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes," that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments with an area of 46 square meters sell very well.
However, it is argued that they can encourage idle lifestyles and discourage developers who want to build large family homes.
But Lim Yu Sun, CEO of home builder EL Developers, says their "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that such apartments sell for a few days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our cash inflows are increasing.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidance to developers who have previously been put off if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step toward boosting the national birth rate, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it seems that they will have little effect.
"People are very stressed, housing is expensive, so is education, and that's why a lot of people are putting it off," says the young manager.
Other people may have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another 20-year-old.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and housing and education costs as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, however much the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to childbearing, Singaporeans have the last word.
Personal offline - Personal online
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Academy of Spanish, this is a private property or "a sphere of privacy that they have the right to protect against any interference."
What is personal for a minor under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when discussing situations online that he probably would not share offline?
elPeriódico interviewed five children aged ten to 15, frequent users of the network.
In four cases, they associated the term with "something very mine," on a personal level, and "password and username" when they applied it to social media.
"My biggest secrets I wouldn't upload to a post," says ten-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of personal on sites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mum may know them, but not the whole world," he says.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I also have fun with my friends.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not mine, or someone who behaves stupidly," he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to post obscene nude photos of people, crimes, or write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has at FB and the nine followers he has on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
The mother is aware, she has the password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them," he adds.
"Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly," he says.
Without hesitation, he replies that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't consider someone who would recommend it to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the latter he admits not knowing the 20 people added to his friend list.
"It doesn't scare me because we have something in common, music, for example," he says.
According to the boy, no one trusted him or asked for his home address or telephone number.
"If I'm pressured or demanded, I'll just delete it from my account," he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experience of what is now known as cyberbullying.
A friend of my friend's was blackmailed on social media.
He was threatened and extorted.
"He never knew who it was," he says.
The victim, according to Jose, did not delete the account.
"Just turned privacy on."
He then explains the sequence of steps to configure the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do it if I didn't like the person or if I wanted to.
"Although I know it's cyberbullying," he confirms.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and education and training specialist, believes that to guide children and teenagers, you need to understand that the purpose of social media is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a tool for searching for information, but the rules of the game have changed with the advent of these sites," she says.
Porras points out that the academic Mark Prensky, a master of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Aborigines and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are the children and young people who were born in the age of technology.
"We are digital immigrants who have to teach them while we are still learning," she says.
He explains that the topic is complex "because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what can or cannot be disseminated, published, or said, at an age when maturity is lacking."
"They also need to be selective when it's most important for them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is to children and teenagers is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it is useless," she adds.
Porras then lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or, would you like it if you posted a photo of you like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign party photos, do you ask other people for permission to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they must behave online as they do offline.
The rules are the same.
"Off the Internet, people behave with respect, responsibility and other principles, just like they should on social media," she said.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, primary education professor and education consultant, explains the need for heads of households to read social media policies faithfully.
By understanding each point, they are well placed to talk to children about the prerequisites of opening an online account.
"For example, the age and what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
According to Gaudia, the key is to remind children the lesson "don't talk to strangers."
UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the announcement of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven binding members.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Assembly of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources in the Office of the President and the Office of the President indicated on the front page that it would be handed over after the closure, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the Peruvian government's website.
In response to questions about the text, they pointed out that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast, in the press room, without a sound, with the message "closed session, no sound."
Little of the information that circulated to reporters was conveyed by the spokesmen of some UNASUR governments that were present at the meeting, but not to the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated throughout the day was a list of participating presidents, which angered hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidential administration sent an e-mail to the media with the summit's "final declaration," but this was Humala's statement, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and this time, despite repeated press demands, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was also not circulated.
The ASPA's official website confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that transmission systems were in place for all journalists, but limited the flow of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which on Monday in The Hague will begin hearing the arguments of both parties in Lima's indictment against Santiago.
"We will respect and implement a judgment that clarifies the differences that we are currently submitting to this international court," Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, pacts, and international tribunals," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake amid the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice comes on the heels of Colombia's challenge this week to the Bogotá Pact, under which it accepted obedience to the Court's verdicts following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it deemed erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and the course of action for 31 projects among South American countries had been approved, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements."
He reported that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America, and to address the risks of natural disasters in a comprehensive and effective manner."
With Europe in crisis, "the economic unification (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our productive base and foresee a better future for our cities," Humala added.
"We have decided to grant privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of parts of South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and creating new economic schemes," the Peruvian president said in a statement read out.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are in Peru and are limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, united, and with good relations between neighbors was another theme highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, Colombia's president, Juan Manuel Santos, said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate respectfully on the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogota.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will reconsider all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Also on the margins of the summit, the bloc's defense ministers met provisionally to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay make up UNASUR, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru holds the interim presidency of the regional bloc.
