Deaths from AIDS today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was announced that his test for AIDS had tested positive.
"I was kind of dumbfounded," he recalls that difficult, despite the doctor's tact, moment.
The young man hid it from his family.
Determined to deal with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn more about it. And his efforts paid off - he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 1990s, this would have been hard to believe - there were too few treatment options, too little knowledge of the disease, too much prejudice.
Thus, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Social Security Institute did not want to say goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so without compromising the quality of life.
Yet, unaware of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already damaged, "depleted" their immune systems and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, "the great achievement so far is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and that of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific journal.
Infection specialist and HIV / AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but that life expectancy and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients have at the onset of diagnosis, with a better life expectancy for non-drug users: up to 30 years with 200 CD4, and up to 50 years with 500 CD4 reported.
Simply put, this means that someone who is diagnosed as HIV positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, "can live without problems until the age of 75," he explained.
To assess this progress, it is worth remembering that Mexicans today have a life expectancy of 76 years on average.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the advent of AIDS, 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths had already been recorded by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still fatalities?
- Personally, it seems to me that the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how things are in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years we have had no shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients arrive very late because they are unaware of their infected condition, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: "Nine out of ten patients come in when they already have some opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, so samples should be made available for detection on a mass scale, for all people who request it."
Experts and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (COESIDA) agree on this proposal, as do patients like Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for testing, motivated only by the fact that his friend had done so and, despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is a common complication.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die anyway, I'd rather hang out three times a week," they say, but not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, exercise, take medication.
Today, his parents only know he has cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I take care of myself and the other person in a responsible way," said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO in order to motivate those who now, in the context of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
Let them be tested if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person while being responsible.
This is his message summarizing the theme of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
The gulf between health-care programs and ordinary citizens is wide, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist in Guadalajara who focuses on HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased, we used to be given one or two, now we are given packets of a hundred, which is very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to a condom," he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
"Why do you want them?" is a popular question that teenagers don't want to hear, with scorn and condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers and health workers, the propagandist said.
I propose that this inefficient distribution be changed; that condoms not only be behind the counter, but that a hundred of them be placed in vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not encouraging promiscuity.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzalez said when asked if condoms could be distributed under his leadership.
"It's not about sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who are already sexually active," he said.
Key data in Jalisco
A total of 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV) have been reported.
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are through sex, 6% through blood, and 2% through the perinatal route.
An estimated 50,000 people may be living with HIV, as for every reported case, there are between four and five people who are unaware of it.
