Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "JR," in the television series "Dallas," in which he portrayed a principled, evil, and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon-predator JR Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of cancer complications, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the studio behind "Dallas."
"Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role that he loved most," his family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving market.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented and I will miss him dearly.
"He was an original person and lived life to the full," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before "Dallas," Hagman became famous on television for his role as a decent type in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie," which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie, played by Barbara Eden, and begins to live with her under the same roof.
He also starred in two comedies that rarely aired, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included roles well received by critics in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully repulsive J.R. that propelled Hagman to the pinnacle of fame.
CBS's drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who shot JR?," designed to create hype around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is nearly killed, has generated international debate and millions of dollars in betting odds.
It also helped draw record audiences to the series at the time.
When the answer was given in an episode in November 1980, an average of 41 million viewers watched it, making "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in history, after the 1983 finale of "MASH," which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was JR's sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
JR stopped her and then threatened her that he would accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be admitted for treatment.
"I know what should be on JR's tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be said: "Here lies honest citizen JR Ewing."
It is the only deal he has lost.
Victoria Principal, also a character in the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, both on and off screen."
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to millions of admirers around the world, and in the hearts of all of us who are fortunate enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on TNT.
Five episodes of the second season have already been completed and a sixth was in production, the channel said.
Warner or TNT have yet to make a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman's departure.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in classics such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the New York theatre scene in the early 1950s, and then served in the British Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
While there, he met and married a young Swedish artist, Maj Axelsson.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the California city of Malibu, home to many celebrities.
In 2001, he called his memoir "Hello Darlin ': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales About My Life."
"I didn't include anything there that I thought would hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told Prensa Asociada at the time.
After his liver transplant, he began promoting organ donation and volunteered at the hospital to help patients with fear.
"I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go for surgery and after," he said in 1996.
I try to offer some consolation, like "don't be afraid, it will be a bit uncomfortable for a short time, but you'll be fine."
He was also an active anti-smoking campaigner and took part in several campaigns.
